N:game-ci-cd-pipeline
D:Design, audit, and harden CI/CD pipelines for Unity and Unreal projects, including build matrices, cache strategy, artifact naming, packaging stages, platform SDK/toolchain checks, and smoke-test gates. Use when a game team needs to set up or repair GitHub Actions or other CI for engine builds, even if they only say "our Unity cloud/GitHub build keeps breaking", "help with Unreal packaging CI", "make our game builds reproducible", "speed up cook / package jobs", or "turn this manual release process into a pipeline".
G:game-development unity unreal ci-cd github-actions build-pipeline release-engineering

U[6]:
  Unity or Unreal teams setting up CI/CD from scratch
  GitHub Actions, Build Automation, or other CI pipelines that are flaky, slow, or hard to debug
  Manual game release processes that need reproducible build, package, and artifact steps
  Requests about cache strategy, large binaries, artifact naming, matrix builds, smoke tests, or packaging gates
  Teams that keep fixing the same cook/package/build problem without changing the pipeline structure
  Publisher, contractor, or technical-lead audits where the team wants a short pipeline hardening brief instead of generic infrastructure advice

S[6]{n,action,details}:
  1,Identify the pipeline scope,Label the request before proposing fixes.
  2,Audit the pipeline through six lenses,Find the weakest lens first.
  3,Classify the primary blocker,Map the situation to one primary blocker and optional secondary blocker.
  4,Build the pipeline brief,Return a concise report with this exact structure:
  5,Tailor the advice to the engine,**For Unity, focus on:** - engine/editor version pinning - package restore stability and Packages/manifest.json / lockfile drift - whether editor-only code or platform defines leak
  6,Ask for the minimum missing evidence when needed,If confidence is low, request the smallest next packet that would materially improve the audit: 1. current workflow file or CI job outline 2. engine version and target platforms 3.
